# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quadtree-octree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A **bounding volume hierarchy** (**BVH**) is a tree structure on a set of geometric objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] All geometric objects, which form the leaf nodes of the tree, are wrapped in bounding volumes.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These nodes are then grouped as small sets and enclosed within larger bounding volumes.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These, in turn, are also grouped and enclosed within other larger bounding volumes in a recursive fashion, eventually resulting in a tree structure with a single bounding volume at the top of the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Bounding volume hierarchies are used to support several operations on sets of geometric objects efficiently, such as in collision detection and ray tracing.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Although wrapping objects in bounding volumes and performing collision tests on them before testing the object geometry itself simplifies the tests and can result in significant performance improvements, the same number of pairwise tests between bounding volumes are still being performed.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] By arranging the bounding volumes into a bounding volume hierarchy, the time complexity (the number of tests performed) can be reduced to logarithmic in the number of objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] With such a hierarchy in place, during collision testing, child volumes do not have to be examined if their parent volumes are not intersected (for example, if the bounding volumes of two bumper cars do not intersect, the bounding volumes of the bumpers themselves need not be checked for collision).
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The choice of bounding volume is determined by a trade-off between two objectives.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the one hand, bounding volumes with a very simple shape can be stored in only a few bytes, and intersection tests and distance computations are simple and fast.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, bounding volumes should fit the corresponding data objects very tightly.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the most commonly used bounding volumes is an axis-aligned minimum bounding box.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box for a given set of data objects is easy to compute, requires only a few bytes to store, and robust intersection tests are easy to implement and extremely fast.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In terms of the structure of BVH, it has to be decided what degree (the number of children) and height to use in the tree representing the BVH.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A tree of a low degree will be of greater height.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] That increases root-to-leaf traversal time.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, less work has to be expended at each visited node to check its children for overlap.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The opposite holds for a high-degree tree: although the tree will be of smaller height, more work is spent at each node.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In practice, binary trees (degree = 2) are by far the most common.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the main reasons is that binary trees are easier to build.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] There are three primary categories of tree construction methods: top-down, bottom-up, and insertion methods.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The most crucial part for this approach is to decide how to partition objects in a node's region among the node's children.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This can be done with a splitting plane to split a node's bounding volume into partitions so that having to traverse many child nodes is minimized.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Simply using the midpoint of volume centroids for splitting might be a sub-optimal choice, as illustrated in the figure, where a big overlap volume occurs.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, good splitting criteria such as the surface-area heuristic (SAH) are often used with equal-size buckets of splitting planes, so that only at these splitting points, re-calculation of SAH is required.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One example for this is the use of a Z-order curve (also known as Morton-order), where clusters can be found by simply taking a linear pass through a Morton-ordered array of leaves.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Given the independent clusters of leaf nodes, sub-trees can be constructed in parallel and then further combined to form higher nodes.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This parallelization makes the BVH construction very fast and can also be implemented in a hybrid manner, where all sub-trees are combined followed by a top-down approach.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Both top-down and bottom-up methods are considered *off-line methods* as they both require all objects to be available before construction starts.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] *Insertion methods* build the tree by inserting one object at a time, starting from an empty tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The insertion location should be chosen that causes the tree to grow as little as possible according to a cost metric.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Insertion methods are considered *on-line methods* since they do not require all objects to be available before construction starts and thus allow updates to be performed at runtime.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] After a BVH tree is constructed, it can then be converted to a compacted form for efficient traversal to improve overall system performance.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The compact representation is often a linear array in memory, where the nodes of the BVH tree are stored in depth-first order.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, for a binary BVH tree, the first child of an internal node will be placed next to itself, and only the offset from the interior node to the index of the second child must be stored explicitly.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The implementation of the traversal can be done without recursive function calls and only a stack is required to store the nodes to be visited next.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The pseudocode provided below is a simple reference for ray tracing applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used in ray tracing to eliminate potential intersection candidates within a scene by omitting geometric objects located in bounding volumes which are not intersected by the current ray.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This only requires a small change in line 11-12 of the above pseudo-code.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Similar optimizations during BVH traversal can be employed when descending into child volumes of the second volume, to restrict further search space and thus reduce traversal time.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs also naturally support inserting and removing objects without full rebuild, but with resulting BVH having usually worse query performance compared to full rebuild.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs can also be combined with scene graph methods, and geometry instancing, to reduce memory usage, improve structure update and full rebuild performance, as well as guide better object or primitive splitting.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used for accelerating collision detection computation.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In the context of cloth simulation, BVHs are used to compute collision between a cloth and itself as well as with other objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Another powerful use case for BVH is pair-wise distance computation.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A naive approach to find the minimum distance between two set of objects would compute the distance between all of the pair-wise combinations.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A BVH allows us to efficiently prune many of the comparisons without needing to compute potentially elaborate distance between the all objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVH can significantly accelerate ray tracing applications by reducing the number of ray-surface intersection calculations.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH operations such as traversal can further accelerate ray-tracing.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Currently, real-time ray tracing is available on multiple platforms.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH is one of the key innovations making it possible.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In 2018, Nvidia introduced RT Cores with their Turing GPU architecture as part of the RTX platform.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] RT Cores are specialized hardware units designed to accelerate BVH traversal and ray-triangle intersection tests.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The combination of these key features enables real-time ray tracing that can be use for video games. as well as design applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] AMD's RDNA (Radeon DNA) architecture, introduced in 2019, has incorporated hardware-accelerated ray tracing since its second iteration, RDNA 2.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The architecture uses dedicated hardware units called Ray Accelerators to perform ray-box and ray-triangle intersection tests, which are crucial for traversing Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVH).
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In RDNA 2 and 3, the shader is responsible for traversing the BVH, while the Ray Accelerators handle intersection tests for box and triangle nodes.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Originally designed to accelerate ray tracing, researchers are now exploring ways to leverage fast BVH traversal to speed up other applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These include determining the containing tetrahedron for a point, enhancing granular matter simulations, and performing nearest neighbor calculations.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Some methods repurpose Nvidia's RT core components by reframing these tasks as ray-tracing problems.
[src:quadtree-octree/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This direction seems promising as substantial speedups in performance are reported across the various applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In computer science, a ***k*-d tree** (short for *k-dimensional tree*) is a space-partitioning data structure for organizing points in a *k*-dimensional space.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] K-dimensional is that which concerns exactly k orthogonal axes or a space of any number of dimensions.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The *k*-d tree is a binary tree in which *every* node is a *k*-dimensional point.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Every non-leaf node can be thought of as implicitly generating a splitting hyperplane that divides the space into two parts, known as half-spaces.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Points to the left of this hyperplane are represented by the left subtree of that node and points to the right of the hyperplane are represented by the right subtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The hyperplane direction is chosen in the following way: every node in the tree is associated with one of the *k* dimensions, with the hyperplane perpendicular to that dimension's axis.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] So, for example, if for a particular split the "x" axis is chosen, all points in the subtree with a smaller "x" value than the node will appear in the left subtree and all points with a larger "x" value will be in the right subtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In such a case, the hyperplane would be set by the x value of the point, and its normal would be the unit x-axis.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Since there are many possible ways to choose axis-aligned splitting planes, there are many different ways to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This method leads to a balanced *k*-d tree, in which each leaf node is approximately the same distance from the root.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] However, balanced trees are not necessarily optimal for all applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Note that it is not *required* to select the median point.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In the case where median points are not selected, there is no guarantee that the tree will be balanced.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] To avoid coding a complex $O(n)$ median-finding algorithm or using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as heapsort or mergesort to sort all *n* points, a popular practice is to sort a *fixed* number of *randomly* *selected* points, and use the median of those points to serve as the splitting plane.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In practice, this technique often results in nicely balanced trees.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Given a list of *n* points, the following algorithm uses a median-finding sort to construct a balanced *k*-d tree containing those points.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] It is common that points "after" the median include only the ones that are strictly greater than the median in the current dimension.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For points that lie on the median in the current dimension, it is possible to define a function that compares them in all dimensions.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In some cases, it is acceptable to let points equal to the median lie on one side of the median, for example, by splitting the points into a "lesser than" subset and a "greater than or equal to" subset.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This algorithm creates the invariant that for any node, all the nodes in the left subtree are on one side of a splitting plane, and all the nodes in the right subtree are on the other side.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Points that lie on the splitting plane may appear on either side.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The splitting plane of a node goes through the point associated with that node (referred to in the code as *node.location*).
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Alternative algorithms for building a balanced *k*-d tree presort the data prior to building the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Then, they maintain the order of the presort during tree construction and hence eliminate the costly step of finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Two such algorithms build a balanced *k*-d tree to sort triangles in order to improve the execution time of ray tracing for three-dimensional computer graphics.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] These algorithms presort *n* triangles prior to building the *k*-d tree, then build the tree in $O(n\log n)$ time in the best case.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] An algorithm that builds a balanced *k*-d tree to sort points has a worst-case complexity of $O(kn\log(n))$ .
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This algorithm presorts *n* points in each of *k* dimensions using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as Heapsort or Mergesort prior to building the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] It then maintains the order of these *k* presorts during tree construction and thereby avoids finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] One adds a new point to a *k*-d tree in the same way as one adds an element to any other search tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] First, traverse the tree, starting from the root and moving to either the left or the right child depending on whether the point to be inserted is on the "left" or "right" side of the splitting plane.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Once you get to the node under which the child should be located, add the new point as either the left or right child of the leaf node, again depending on which side of the node's splitting plane contains the new node.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Adding points in this manner can cause the tree to become unbalanced, leading to decreased tree performance.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The rate of tree performance degradation is dependent upon the spatial distribution of tree points being added, and the number of points added in relation to the tree size.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] If a tree becomes too unbalanced, it may need to be re-balanced to restore the performance of queries that rely on the tree balancing, such as nearest neighbour searching.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] To remove a point from an existing *k*-d tree without breaking the invariant, the easiest way is to form the set of all nodes and leaves from the children of the target node and recreate that part of the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Another approach is to find a replacement for the point removed.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] First, find the node R that contains the point to be removed.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For the base case, where R is a leaf node, no replacement is required.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For the general case, find a replacement point, say p , from the subtree rooted at R .
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For finding a replacement point, if R discriminates on x (say) and R has a right child, find the point with the minimum x value from the subtree rooted at the right child.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, find the point with the maximum x value from the subtree rooted at the left child.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Balancing a *k*-d tree requires care because *k*-d trees are sorted in multiple dimensions, so the tree-rotation technique cannot be used to balance them as this may break the invariant.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Several variants of balanced *k*-d trees exist.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] They include divided *k*-d tree, pseudo *k*-d tree, K-D-B-tree, hB-tree and Bkd-tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Many of these variants are adaptive k-d trees.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour search (NN) algorithm aims to find the point in the tree that is nearest to a given input point.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This search can be done efficiently by using the tree properties to quickly eliminate large portions of the search space.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Once the algorithm reaches a leaf node, it checks the node point and if the distance is better than the "current best", that node point is saved as the "current best".
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The algorithm checks whether there could be any points on the other side of the splitting plane that are closer to the search point than the current best.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In concept, this is done by intersecting the splitting hyperplane with a hypersphere around the search point that has a radius equal to the current nearest distance.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Since the hyperplanes are all axis-aligned this is implemented as a simple comparison to see whether the distance between the splitting coordinate of the search point and current node is less than the distance (overall coordinates) from the search point to the current best.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] If the hypersphere doesn't intersect the splitting plane, then the algorithm continues walking up the tree, and the entire branch on the other side of that node is eliminated.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] When the algorithm finishes this process for the root node, then the search is complete.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Generally the algorithm uses squared distances for comparison to avoid computing square roots.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Additionally, it can save computation by holding the squared current best distance in a variable for comparison.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The algorithm can be extended in several ways by simple modifications.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] It can provide the *k* nearest neighbours to a point by maintaining *k* current bests instead of just one.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] A branch is only eliminated when *k* points have been found and the branch cannot have points closer than any of the *k* current bests.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] It can also be converted to an approximation algorithm to run faster.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For example, approximate nearest neighbour searching can be achieved by simply setting an upper bound on the number of points to examine in the tree or by interrupting the search process based upon a real time clock (which may be more appropriate in hardware implementations).
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour for points that are already in the tree can be achieved by not updating the refinement for nodes that give zero distance.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] As a result, this has the downside of discarding points that are not unique but are co-located with the original search point.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Approximate nearest neighbour is useful in real-time applications such as robotics due to the significant speed increase gained by not searching for the best point exhaustively.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] One of its implementations is best-bin-first search.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] A range search searches for ranges of parameters.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For example, if a tree is storing values corresponding to income and age, then a range search might be something like looking for all members of the tree which have an age between 20 and 50 years and an income between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Since k-d trees divide the range of a domain in half at each level of the tree, they are useful for performing range searches.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Analyses of binary search trees has found that the worst case time for range search in a *k*-dimensional *k*-d tree containing *n* nodes is given by the following equation.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In low-dimensional spaces, the nearest point is an $O(\log(n))$ operation on average, in the case of randomly distributed points, although analysis in general is tricky.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In high-dimensional spaces, the curse of dimensionality causes the algorithm to need to visit many more branches than in lower-dimensional spaces.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In particular, when the number of points is only slightly higher than the number of dimensions, the algorithm is only slightly better than a linear search of all of the points.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] As a general rule, if the dimensionality is *k*, the number of points in the data, *n*, should be $n\gg 2^{k}$ .
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, when *k*-d trees are used with high-dimensional data, most of the points in the tree will be evaluated and the efficiency is no better than exhaustive search, and, if a good-enough fast answer is required, approximate nearest-neighbour methods should be used instead.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] (In the worst case, consider a cloud of points distributed on the surface of a sphere centered at the origin.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This may result in a nearest neighbor search failing to return a nearest neighbor, which means no points are within this maximum distance from the query point.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Instead of points, a *k*-d tree can also contain rectangles or hyperrectangles.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Thus range search becomes the problem of returning all rectangles intersecting the search rectangle.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The tree is constructed the usual way with all the rectangles at the leaves.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] In an orthogonal range search, the *opposite* coordinate is used when comparing against the median.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] For example, if the current level is split along xhigh, we check the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] If the median is less than the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle, then no rectangle in the left branch can ever intersect with the search rectangle and so can be pruned.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Otherwise both branches should be traversed.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] See also interval tree, which is a 1-dimensional special case.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] It is also possible to define a *k*-d tree with points stored solely in leaves.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This form of *k*-d tree allows a variety of split mechanics other than the standard median split.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] The midpoint splitting rule selects on the middle of the longest axis of the space being searched, regardless of the distribution of points.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] This guarantees that the aspect ratio will be at most 2:1, but the depth is dependent on the distribution of points.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] A variation, called sliding-midpoint, only splits on the middle if there are points on both sides of the split.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Otherwise, it splits on point nearest to the middle.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Maneewongvatana and Mount show that this offers "good enough" performance on common data sets.
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Using sliding-midpoint, an approximate nearest neighbour query can be answered in $O\left({\tfrac {1}{{\epsilon \ }^{d}}}\log n\right)$ .
[src:quadtree-octree/k-d-tree] Approximate range counting can be answered in $O\left(\log n+{\left({\tfrac {1}{\epsilon \ }}\right)}^{d}\right)$ with this method.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] An **octree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly eight children.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Octrees are most often used to partition a three-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into eight octants.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Octrees are the three-dimensional analog of quadtrees.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The word is derived from *oct* (Greek root meaning "eight") + *tree*.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Octrees are often used in 3D graphics and 3D game engines.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Each node in an octree subdivides the space it represents into eight octants.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] In a point region (PR) octree (analogous to a point quadtree), the node stores an explicit three-dimensional point, which is the "center" of the subdivision for that node; the point defines one of the corners for each of the eight children.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] In a matrix-based (MX) octree (analogous to a region quadtree), the subdivision point is implicitly the center of the space the node represents.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The root node of a PR octree can represent infinite space; the root node of an MX octree must represent a finite bounded space so that the implicit centers are well-defined.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Note that octrees are not the same as *k*-d trees: *k*-d trees split along a dimension and octrees split around a point.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Also *k*-d trees are always binary, which is not the case for octrees.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] By using a depth-first search the nodes are to be traversed and only required surfaces are to be viewed.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] A spatial subdivision much like an octree was used in 1934, in the Whitney covering lemma in mathematics.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The octree color quantization algorithm, invented by Gervautz and Purgathofer in 1988, encodes image color data as an octree up to nine levels deep.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Octrees are used because $2^{3}=8$ and there are three color components in the RGB system.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The node index to branch out from at the top level is determined by a formula that uses the most significant bits of the red, green, and blue color components, e.g.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The next lower level uses the next bit significance, and so on.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Less significant bits are sometimes ignored to reduce the tree size.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The algorithm is highly memory efficient because the tree's size can be limited.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The bottom level of the octree consists of leaf nodes that accrue color data not represented in the tree; these nodes initially contain single bits.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] If much more than the desired number of palette colors are entered into the octree, its size can be continually reduced by seeking out a bottom-level node and averaging its bit data up into a leaf node, pruning part of the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Once sampling is complete, exploring all routes in the tree down to the leaf nodes, taking note of the bits along the way, will yield approximately the required number of colors.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The example recursive algorithm outline below (MATLAB syntax) decomposes an array of 3-dimensional points into octree style bins.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The implementation begins with a single bin surrounding all given points, which then recursively subdivides into its 8 octree regions.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Recursion is stopped when a given exit condition is met.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Taking the full list of colors of a 24-bit RGB image as point input to the Octree point decomposition implementation outlined above, the following example show the results of octree color quantization.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] The first image is the original (532818 distinct colors), while the second is the quantized image (184 distinct colors) using octree decomposition, with each pixel assigned the color at the center of the octree bin in which it falls.
[src:quadtree-octree/octree] Alternatively, final colors could be chosen at the centroid of all colors in each octree bin, however this added computation has very little effect on the visual result.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A **quadtree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly four children.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Quadtrees are the two-dimensional analog of octrees and are most often used to partition a two-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into four quadrants or regions.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The data associated with a leaf cell varies by application, but the leaf cell represents a "unit of interesting spatial information".
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The subdivided regions may be square or rectangular, or may have arbitrary shapes.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Although similar subdivisions were used much earlier (for instance in the Whitney covering lemma of 1934), this data structure was named a quadtree by Raphael Finkel and J.L.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A similar partitioning is also known as a *Q-tree*.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A **tree-pyramid** (**T-pyramid**) is a "complete" tree; every node of the T-pyramid has four child nodes except leaf nodes; all leaves are on the same level, the level that corresponds to individual pixels in the image.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The data in a tree-pyramid can be stored compactly in an array as an implicit data structure similar to the way a binary heap can store a complete binary tree compactly in an array.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Quadtrees may be classified according to the type of data they represent, including areas, points, lines and curves.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Quadtrees may also be classified by whether the shape of the tree is independent of the order in which data is processed.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The following are common types of quadtrees.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The region quadtree represents a partition of space in two dimensions by decomposing the region into four equal quadrants, subquadrants, and so on with each leaf node containing data corresponding to a specific subregion.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It can be also interpreted as a method for "subpaving the region", based on set of hierarchical grids; or as a method of image compression, when an image is discretizated as a mosaic of "equal color regions".
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Each node in the tree either has exactly four children, or has no children (a leaf node).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The height of quadtrees that follow this decomposition strategy (i.e. subdividing subquadrants as long as there is interesting data in the subquadrant for which more refinement is desired) is sensitive to and dependent on the spatial distribution of interesting areas in the space being decomposed.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A region quadtree with a depth of n may be used to represent an image consisting of 2n × 2n pixels, where each pixel value is 0 or 1.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The root node represents the entire image region.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If the pixels in any region are not entirely 0s or 1s, it is subdivided.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] In this application, each leaf node represents a block of pixels that are all 0s or all 1s.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Note the potential savings in terms of space when these trees are used for storing images; images often have many regions of considerable size that have the same colour value throughout.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Rather than store a big 2-D array of every pixel in the image, a quadtree can capture the same information potentially many divisive levels higher than the pixel-resolution sized cells that we would otherwise require.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The tree resolution and overall size is bounded by the pixel and image sizes.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A region quadtree may also be used as a variable resolution representation of a data field.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For example, the temperatures in an area may be stored as a quadtree, with each leaf node storing the average temperature over the subregion it represents.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The point quadtree is an adaptation of a binary tree used to represent two-dimensional point data.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It shares the features of all quadtrees but is a true tree as the center of a subdivision is always on a point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It is often very efficient in comparing two-dimensional, ordered data points, usually operating in O(log n) time.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Point quadtrees are worth mentioning for completeness, but they have been surpassed by *k*-d trees as tools for generalized binary search.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Point quadtrees with random insertion have been studied under the name **weighted planar stochastic lattices**.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Point quadtrees are constructed as follows.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Given the next point to insert, we find the cell in which it lies and add it to the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The new point is added such that the cell that contains it is divided into quadrants by the vertical and horizontal lines that run through the point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Consequently, cells are rectangular but not necessarily square.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] In these trees, each node contains one of the input points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Since the division of the plane is decided by the order of point-insertion, the tree's height is sensitive to and dependent on insertion order.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Inserting in a "bad" order can lead to a tree of height linear in the number of input points (at which point it becomes a linked-list).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If the point-set is static, pre-processing can be done to create a tree of balanced height.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A node of a point quadtree is similar to a node of a binary tree, with the major difference being that it has four pointers (one for each quadrant) instead of two ("left" and "right") as in an ordinary binary tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Also a key is usually decomposed into two parts, referring to x and y coordinates.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Point-region (PR) quadtrees are very similar to region quadtrees.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The difference is the type of information stored about the cells.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] In a region quadtree, a uniform value is stored that applies to the entire area of the cell of a leaf.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The cells of a PR quadtree, however, store a list of points that exist within the cell of a leaf.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] As mentioned previously, for trees following this decomposition strategy the height depends on the spatial distribution of the points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Like the point quadtree, the PR quadtree may also have a linear height when given a "bad" set.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Edge quadtrees (much like PM quadtrees) are used to store lines rather than points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Curves are approximated by subdividing cells to a very fine resolution, specifically until there is a single line segment per cell.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Near corners/vertices, edge quadtrees will continue dividing until they reach their maximum level of decomposition.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This can result in extremely unbalanced trees which may defeat the purpose of indexing.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The polygonal map quadtree (or PM Quadtree) is a variation of quadtree which is used to store collections of polygons that may be degenerate (meaning that they have isolated vertices or edges).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] A big difference between PM quadtrees and edge quadtrees is that the cell under consideration is not subdivided if the segments meet at a vertex in the cell.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] There are three main classes of PM Quadtrees, which vary depending on what information they store within each black node.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] PM3 quadtrees can store any amount of non-intersecting edges and at most one point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] PM2 quadtrees are the same as PM3 quadtrees except that all edges must share the same end point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Finally PM1 quadtrees are similar to PM2, but black nodes can contain a point and its edges or just a set of edges that share a point, but you cannot have a point and a set of edges that do not contain the point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This section summarizes a subsection from a book by Sariel Har-Peled.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If we were to store every node corresponding to a subdivided cell, we may end up storing a lot of empty nodes.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We can cut down on the size of such sparse trees by only storing subtrees whose leaves have interesting data (i.e.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We can actually cut down on the size even further.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] When we only keep important subtrees, the pruning process may leave long paths in the tree where the intermediate nodes have degree two (a link to one parent and one child).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It turns out that we only need to store the node u at the beginning of this path (and associate some meta-data with it to represent the removed nodes) and attach the subtree rooted at its end to u .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It is still possible for these compressed trees to have a linear height when given "bad" input points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Although we trim a lot of the tree when we perform this compression, it is still possible to achieve logarithmic-time search, insertion, and deletion by taking advantage of *Z*-order curves.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The *Z*-order curve maps each cell of the full quadtree (and hence even the compressed quadtree) in $O(1)$ time to a one-dimensional line (and maps it back in $O(1)$ time too), creating a total order on the elements.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Therefore, we can store the quadtree in a data structure for ordered sets (in which we store the nodes of the tree).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We must state a reasonable assumption before we continue: we assume that given two real numbers $\alpha ,\beta \in [0,1)$ expressed as binary, we can compute in $O(1)$ time the index of the first bit in which they differ.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We also assume that we can compute in $O(1)$ time the lowest common ancestor of two points/cells in the quadtree and establish their relative *Z*-ordering, and we can compute the floor function in $O(1)$ time.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] With these assumptions, point location of a given point q (i.e. determining the cell that would contain q ), insertion, and deletion operations can all be performed in $O(\log {n})$ time (i.e. the time it takes to do a search in the underlying ordered set data structure).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Else, find what would have been the lowest common ancestor of the point q and the cell v in an uncompressed quadtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Find the existing cell in the compressed tree that comes before u in the *Z*-order and return it.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Without going into specific details, to perform insertions and deletions we first do a point location for the thing we want to insert/delete, and then insert/delete it.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Care must be taken to reshape the tree as appropriate, creating and removing nodes as needed.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Quadtrees, particularly the region quadtree, have lent themselves well to image processing applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We will limit our discussion to binary image data, though region quadtrees and the image processing operations performed on them are just as suitable for colour images.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] One of the advantages of using quadtrees for image manipulation is that the set operations of union and intersection can be done simply and quickly.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Given two binary images, the image union (also called *overlay*) produces an image wherein a pixel is black if either of the input images has a black pixel in the same location.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] That is, a pixel in the output image is white only when the corresponding pixel in *both* input images is white, otherwise the output pixel is black.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Rather than do the operation pixel by pixel, we can compute the union more efficiently by leveraging the quadtree's ability to represent multiple pixels with a single node.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For the purposes of discussion below, if a subtree contains both black and white pixels we will say that the root of that subtree is coloured grey.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The algorithm works by traversing the two input quadtrees ( $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ ) while building the output quadtree T .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Informally, the algorithm is as follows.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Consider the nodes $v_{1}\in T_{1}$ and $v_{2}\in T_{2}$ corresponding to the same region in the images.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] While this algorithm works, it does not by itself guarantee a minimally sized quadtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For example, consider the result if we were to union a checkerboard (where every tile is a pixel) of size $2^{k}\times 2^{k}$ with its complement.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The result is a giant black square which should be represented by a quadtree with just the root node (coloured black), but instead the algorithm produces a full 4-ary tree of depth k .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] To fix this, we perform a bottom-up traversal of the resulting quadtree where we check if the four children nodes have the same colour, in which case we replace their parent with a leaf of the same colour.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The intersection of two images is almost the same algorithm.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] One way to think about the intersection of the two images is that we are doing a union with respect to the *white* pixels.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] As such, to perform the intersection we swap the mentions of black and white in the union algorithm.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Consider two neighbouring black pixels in a binary image.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] They are *adjacent* if they share a bounding horizontal or vertical edge.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] In general, two black pixels are *connected* if one can be reached from the other by moving only to adjacent pixels (i.e. there is a path of black pixels between them where each consecutive pair is adjacent).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Each maximal set of connected black pixels is a *connected component*.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Using the quadtree representation of images, Samet showed how we can find and label these connected components in time proportional to the size of the quadtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This algorithm can also be used for polygon colouring.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] To simplify the discussion, let us assume the children of a node in the quadtree follow the *Z*-order (SW, NW, SE, NE).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Since we can count on this structure, for any cell we know how to navigate the quadtree to find the adjacent cells in the different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Step one is accomplished with a post-order traversal of the quadtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For each black leaf v we look at the node or nodes representing cells that are Northern neighbours and Eastern neighbours (i.e. the Northern and Eastern cells that share edges with the cell of v ).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Since the tree is organized in *Z*-order, we have the invariant that the Southern and Western neighbours have already been taken care of and accounted for.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Let the Northern or Eastern neighbour currently under consideration be u .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Step two can be accomplished using the union-find data structure.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We start with each unique label as a separate set.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For every equivalence relation noted in the first step, we union the corresponding sets.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Afterwards, each distinct remaining set will be associated with a distinct connected component in the image.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Step three performs another post-order traversal.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This time, for each black node v we use the union-find's *find* operation (with the old label of v ) to find and assign v its new label (associated with the connected component of which v is part).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This section summarizes a chapter from a book by Har-Peled and de Berg et al.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Mesh generation is essentially the triangulation of a point set for which further processing may be performed.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] As such, it is desirable for the resulting triangulation to have certain properties (like non-uniformity, triangles that are not "too skinny", large triangles in sparse areas and small triangles in dense ones, etc.) to make further processing quicker and less error-prone.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Quadtrees built on the point set can be used to create meshes with these desired properties.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Consider a leaf of the quadtree and its corresponding cell v .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We say v is *balanced* (for mesh generation) if the cell's sides are intersected by the corner points of neighbouring cells at most once on each side.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This means that the quadtree levels of leaves adjacent to v differ by at most one from the level of v .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] When this is true for all leaves, we say the whole quadtree is balanced (for mesh generation).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Consider the cell v and the $5\times 5$ neighbourhood of same-sized cells centred at v .
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We call this neighbourhood the *extended cluster*.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We say the quadtree is *well-balanced* if it is balanced, and for every leaf u that contains a point of the point set, its extended cluster is also in the quadtree and the extended cluster contains no other point of the point set.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For every leaf, if there is a neighbour that is too large, subdivide the neighbour.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This is repeated until the tree is balanced.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We also make sure that for a leaf with a point in it, the nodes for each leaf's extended cluster are in the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For every leaf node v that contains a point, if the extended cluster contains another point, we further subdivide the tree and rebalance as necessary.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If we needed to subdivide, for each child u of v we ensure the nodes of u 's extended cluster are in the tree (and re-balance as required).
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Repeat the previous step until the tree is well-balanced.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Transform the quadtree into a triangulation.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] We consider the corner points of the tree cells as vertices in our triangulation.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Before the transformation step we have a bunch of boxes with points in some of them.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The remaining squares are triangulated according to some simple rules.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For each regular square (no points within and no corner points in its sides), introduce the diagonal.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] Due to the way in which we separated points with the well-balancing property, no square with a corner intersecting a side is one that was warped.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] As such, we can triangulate squares with intersecting corners as follows.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If there is one intersected side, the square becomes three triangles by adding the long diagonals connecting the intersection with opposite corners.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] If there are four intersected sides, we split the square in half by adding an edge between two of the four intersections, and then connect these two endpoints to the remaining two intersection points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] For the other squares, we introduce a point in the middle and connect it to all four corners of the square as well as each intersection point.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] At the end of it all, we have a nice triangulated mesh of our point set built from a quadtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The following pseudo code shows one means of implementing a quadtree which handles only points.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] It is assumed these structures are used.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] This class represents both one quad tree and the node where it is rooted.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The following method inserts a point into the appropriate quad of a quadtree, splitting if necessary.
[src:quadtree-octree/quadtree] The following method finds all points contained within a range.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The key idea of the data structure is to group nearby objects and represent them with their minimum bounding rectangle in the next higher level of the tree; the "R" in R-tree is for rectangle.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Since all objects lie within this bounding rectangle, a query that does not intersect the bounding rectangle also cannot intersect any of the contained objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] At the leaf level, each rectangle describes a single object; at higher levels the aggregation includes an increasing number of objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] This can also be seen as an increasingly coarse approximation of the data set.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Similar to the B-tree, the R-tree is also a balanced search tree (so all leaf nodes are at the same depth), organizes the data in pages, and is designed for storage on disk (as used in databases).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Each page can contain a maximum number of entries, often denoted as M .
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] It also guarantees a minimum fill (except for the root node), however best performance has been experienced with a minimum fill of 30%–40% of the maximum number of entries (B-trees guarantee 50% page fill, and B*-trees even 66%).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The reason for this is the more complex balancing required for spatial data as opposed to linear data stored in B-trees.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] As with most trees, the searching algorithms (e.g., intersection, containment, nearest neighbor search) are rather simple.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The key idea is to use the bounding boxes to decide whether or not to search inside a subtree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] In this way, most of the nodes in the tree are never read during a search.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Like B-trees, R-trees are suitable for large data sets and databases, where nodes can be paged to memory when needed, and the whole tree cannot be kept in main memory.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Even if data can be fit in memory (or cached), the R-trees in most practical applications will usually provide performance advantages over naive check of all objects when the number of objects is more than few hundred or so.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] However, for in-memory applications, there are similar alternatives that can provide slightly better performance or be simpler to implement in practice.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] To maintain in-memory computing for R-tree in a computer cluster where computing nodes are connected by a network, researchers have used RDMA (Remote Direct Memory Access) to implement data-intensive applications under R-tree in a distributed environment.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] This approach is scalable for increasingly large applications and achieves high throughput and low latency performance for R-tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The key difficulty of R-tree is to build an efficient tree that on one hand is balanced (so the leaf nodes are at the same height) on the other hand the rectangles do not cover too much empty space and do not overlap too much (so that during search, fewer subtrees need to be processed).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] For example, the original idea for inserting elements to obtain an efficient tree is to always insert into the subtree that requires least enlargement of its bounding box.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Once that page is full, the data is split into two sets that should cover the minimal area each.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Most of the research and improvements for R-trees aims at improving the way the tree is built and can be grouped into two objectives: building an efficient tree from scratch (known as bulk-loading) and performing changes on an existing tree (insertion and deletion).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] R-trees do not guarantee good worst-case performance, but generally perform well with real-world data.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The (bulk-loaded) Priority R-tree variant of the R-tree is worst-case optimal, but due to its increased complexity it has remained confined to theoretical study and has not received much attention in practical applications.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] When data is organized in an R-tree, the neighbors within a given distance r and the k nearest neighbors (for any Lp-Norm) of all points can efficiently be computed using a spatial join.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] This is beneficial for many algorithms based on such queries, for example the Local Outlier Factor.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering is a cluster analysis algorithm that uses the R-tree structure for a similar kind of spatial join to efficiently compute an OPTICS clustering.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Data in R-trees is organized in pages that can have a variable number of entries (up to some pre-defined maximum, and usually above a minimum fill).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Each entry within a non-leaf node stores two pieces of data: a way of identifying a child node, and the bounding box of all entries within this child node.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Leaf nodes store the data required for each child, often a point or bounding box representing the child and an external identifier for the child.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] For point data, the leaf entries can be just the points themselves.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] For polygon data (that often requires the storage of large polygons) the common setup is to store only the MBR (minimum bounding rectangle) of the polygon along with a unique identifier in the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The search process in an R-tree embodies a two-phase approach that aligns with the Filter and Refine Principle (FRP).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] In this structure, the internal nodes serve as an initial filter by quickly excluding regions of space that do not intersect the query, while the leaf nodes provide a refined, precise evaluation by storing the actual spatial objects.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Specifically, in range searching, the input is a search rectangle (Query box).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Searching is quite similar to searching in a B+ tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The search starts from the root node of the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Every internal node contains a set of rectangles and pointers to the corresponding child node and every leaf node contains the rectangles of spatial objects (the pointer to some spatial object can be there).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] For every rectangle in a node, it has to be decided if it overlaps the search rectangle or not.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] If yes, the corresponding child node has to be searched also.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Searching is done like this in a recursive manner until all overlapping nodes have been traversed.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] When a leaf node is reached, the contained bounding boxes (rectangles) are tested against the search rectangle and their objects (if there are any) are put into the result set if they lie within the search rectangle.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] For priority search such as nearest neighbor search, the query consists of a point or rectangle.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The root node is inserted into the priority queue.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Until the queue is empty or the desired number of results have been returned the search continues by processing the nearest entry in the queue.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Tree nodes are expanded and their children reinserted.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Leaf entries are returned when encountered in the queue.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] This approach can be used with various distance metrics, including great-circle distance for geographic data.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] To insert an object, the tree is traversed recursively from the root node.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] At each step, all rectangles in the current directory node are examined, and a candidate is chosen using a heuristic such as choosing the rectangle which requires least enlargement.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The search then descends into this page, until reaching a leaf node.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] If the leaf node is full, it must be split before the insertion is made.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Again, since an exhaustive search is too expensive, a heuristic is employed to split the node into two.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Adding the newly created node to the previous level, this level can again overflow, and these overflows can propagate up to the root node; when this node also overflows, a new root node is created and the tree has increased in height.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The algorithm needs to decide in which subtree to insert.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] When a data object is fully contained in a single rectangle, the choice is clear.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] When there are multiple options or rectangles in need of enlargement, the choice can have a significant impact on the performance of the tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The objects are inserted into the subtree that needs the least enlargement.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] A Mixture heuristic is employed throughout.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] What happens next is it tries to minimize the overlap (in case of ties, prefer least enlargement and then least area); at the higher levels, it behaves similar to the R-tree, but on ties again preferring the subtree with smaller area.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] The decreased overlap of rectangles in the R*-tree is one of the key benefits over the traditional R-tree.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Since redistributing all objects of a node into two nodes has an exponential number of options, a heuristic needs to be employed to find the best split.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] In the classic R-tree, Guttman proposed two such heuristics, called QuadraticSplit and LinearSplit.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] In quadratic split, the algorithm searches for the pair of rectangles that is the worst combination to have in the same node, and puts them as initial objects into the two new groups.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] It then searches for the entry which has the strongest preference for one of the groups (in terms of area increase) and assigns the object to this group until all objects are assigned (satisfying the minimum fill).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] In addition to having a more advanced splitting heuristic, the R*-tree also tries to avoid splitting a node by reinserting some of the node members, which is similar to the way a B-tree balances overflowing nodes.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] This was shown to also reduce overlap and thus increase tree performance.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Finally, the X-tree can be seen as a R*-tree variant that can also decide to not split a node, but construct a so-called super-node containing all the extra entries, when it doesn't find a good split (in particular for high-dimensional data).
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Deleting an entry from a page may require updating the bounding rectangles of parent pages.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] However, when a page is underfull, it will not be balanced with its neighbors.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] Instead, the page will be dissolved and all its children (which may be subtrees, not only leaf objects) will be reinserted.
[src:quadtree-octree/r-tree] If during this process the root node has a single element, the tree height can decrease.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] In geometry, **space partitioning** is the process of dividing an entire space (usually a Euclidean space) into two or more disjoint subsets (see also partition of a set).
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] In other words, space partitioning divides a space into non-overlapping regions.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Any point in the space can then be identified to lie in exactly one of the regions.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Space-partitioning systems are often hierarchical, meaning that a space (or a region of space) is divided into several regions, and then the same space-partitioning system is recursively applied to each of the regions thus created.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] The regions can be organized into a tree, called a **space-partitioning tree**.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Most space-partitioning systems use planes (or, in higher dimensions, hyperplanes) to divide space: points on one side of the plane form one region, and points on the other side form another.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Points exactly on the plane are usually arbitrarily assigned to one or the other side.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Recursively partitioning space using planes in this way produces a BSP tree, one of the most common forms of space partitioning.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is particularly important in computer graphics, especially heavily used in ray tracing, where it is frequently used to organize the objects in a virtual scene.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] A typical scene may contain millions of polygons.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Performing a ray/polygon intersection test with each would be a very computationally expensive task.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Space partitioning is also often used in scanline algorithms to eliminate the polygons out of the camera's viewing frustum, limiting the number of polygons processed by the pipeline.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] There is also a usage in collision detection: determining whether two objects are close to each other can be much faster using space partitioning.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] In integrated circuit design, an important step is design rule check.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] This step ensures that the completed design is manufacturable.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] The check involves rules that specify widths and spacings and other geometry patterns.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] A modern design can have billions of polygons that represent wires and transistors.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Efficient checking relies heavily on geometry query.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] For example, a rule may specify that any polygon must be at least *n* nanometers from any other polygon.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] This is converted into a geometry query by enlarging a polygon by *n/2* at all sides and query to find all intersecting polygons.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] The number of components in a space partition plays a central role in some results in probability theory.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] There are many studies and applications where Geographical Spatial Reality is partitioned by hydrological criteria, administrative criteria, mathematical criteria or many others.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] In the context of cartography and GIS - Geographic Information System, is common to identify cells of the partition by standard codes.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] For example the for HUC code identifying hydrographical basins and sub-basins, ISO 3166-2 codes identifying countries and its subdivisions, or arbitrary DGGs - discrete global grids identifying quadrants or locations.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Suppose the n-dimensional Euclidean space is partitioned by r hyperplanes that are $(n-1)$ -dimensional.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] What is the number of components in the partition?
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] The largest number of components is attained when the hyperplanes are in general position, i.e, no two are parallel and no three have the same intersection.
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] Denote this maximum number of components by $Comp(n,r)$ .
[src:quadtree-octree/space-partitioning] perpendicular hyperplanes; each additional hyperplane divides each existing component to 2).
